                            1
                        Share This Story!Let friends in your social network know what you are reading aboutFacebookEmailTwitterGoogle+LinkedInPinterestMatthew Barzun is something different for the BritsEnvoy Matthew Barzun's rock, blue jeans and Kentucky hospitality bring new day to London diplomacyPost to FacebookMatthew Barzun is something different for the Brits Envoy Matthew Barzun's rock, blue jeans and Kentucky hospitality bring new day to London diplomacy  Check out this story on courier-journal.com: http://cjky.it/1CjJEVO
                            {#
                            
                            #}
                        CancelSendSent!A link has been sent to your friend's email address.Posted!A link has been posted to your Facebook feed. Join the ConversationTo find out more about Facebook commenting please read the Conversation Guidelines and FAQsSubscribe TodayLog InSubscribed, but don't have a login?Activate your digital access.Matthew Barzun is something different for the Brits
        Louisville
    
            Published 1:48 p.m. ET March 28, 2015 | Updated 11:54 a.m. ET March 30, 2015Buy PhotoMatthew Barzun(Photo: James R. Carroll/The Courier-Journal)Buy PhotoStory HighlightsMatthew Barzun, the American ambassador to Great Britain, talks about the special relationship and his role in keeping it aliveBarzun and his wife, Brooke, have been a hit in the British capital, bringing a new level of informality and fun to the ambassador's residence, Winfield House, in Regent's Park
            
                40
            
        CONNECTTWEET
            
                1
            
        LINKEDINCOMMENTEMAILMOREWASHINGTON –  On a train from London to Hull, Matthew Barzun decided to check the web to see what famous people were from the Yorkshire city he was about the visit.The former Louisville Internet entrepreneur knows his way around mathematics and theory, so he was excited to discover that John Venn was from Hull.Venn devised a diagram of intersecting circles now known as, logically, the Venn diagram. The philosopher and logician's contribution is used in computer science, among other fields.Barzun, 44, now the youthful and energetic United States ambassador to the United Kingdom, was so excited recounting his story last week during an interview with The Courier-Journal in a conference room at the State Department that he got up and drew a Venn diagram on the white board."My first thought was I probably owe that guy royalties, because in my Internet days I'd drawn so many Venn diagrams," Barzun joked, retelling the story.But there was a broader point to this story.He labeled one circle "US" and the other "UK" and the intersecting space in the middle is the special relationship the two nations have enjoyed for more than a century, from joining together to help win World War II to the alliance engaged in current negotiations with Iran over its nuclear program.Indeed, Barzun said the mere act of looking up John Venn got him thinking more about the common bonds between Great Britain and the United States."I'm on a train, right?" the ambassador began. "Steam locomotion - invented by Brits. It was actually an American who said we should use this for public transit and had a whole plan but couldn't get it done in America because it wasn't developed enough. Then it did, of course, happen in the UK and then it happened in America. I'm using an iPhone, an American product designed by a Brit from Newcastle. I log onto the Internet, invented by Americans, quickly adopted by the UK. Log on to the worldwide web, invented by a Brit, commercialized in America. To use Wikipedia (to find John Venn), founded by an American from Alabama who now lives two blocks away from me in London. So I just thought, you know? There's a happy Venn diagram."Barzun was making one of his infrequent visits home to Kentucky and to Washington, and it is clear he has embraced his role as the nation's most prominent ambassador.He has been in his post since 2013. A key fundraiser for President Barack Obama, Barzun previously served as the U.S. ambassador to Sweden.Barzun and his wife, Brooke, have been a hit in the British capital, bringing a new level of informality and fun to the ambassador's residence, Winfield House, in Regent's Park. The Barzuns hosted a record 10,750 visitors in the residence last year. Those who were at parties might have been treated to a hot new indie band the ambassador likes, or songs with Annie Lennox at the keyboards. Jeans are allowed.The Financial Times credited the American envoy with bringing "a bracing informality to the practice of London diplomacy."The London Evening Standard ran a glowing piece on the Barzuns in February. Much of the story focused on Brooke Barzun under a headline that called her "the hostess with the mostest.""The ambassador and his wife could make Scott and Zelda Fitzgerald look like party poopers," the newspaper enthused. "Now they are using their party power to push social change."The Barzuns recently hosted a session in the residence on women's rights in the workplace.The ambassador also has become known in London as a fervent collector of vinyl records, which he puts on the turntable at gatherings. So that earned him praise for "vinyl diplomacy."Barzun said he simply has tried to put into practice in London what he absorbed after moving to Louisville in 2000: "It's that wonderful blend of southern hospitality meets Midwestern openness…We try to do that in all of our interactions in the UK."When he was first headed to the Court of St. James's, some people advised him to park the term "special relationship," saying it was hackneyed."So I thought about that for a moment, and I think they are totally wrong. I think it really is special," Barzun said, noting that next year will mark the 70th anniversary of Winston Churchill's coining of the "special relationship" phrase in his famous "Iron Curtain" speech in Fulton, Mo. "And it remains today vibrant, vital."Americans may not realize that 1 million people on this side of the Atlantic work for British companies. Likewise, 1 million British workers are employed by American companies.But the relationship goes beyond business and trade and cultural similarities."We mean the same things when we say as, President Obama did when he visited in 2011, that we want to make the world more peaceful, more prosperous, more just. We mean the same things by those important values," Barzun said. "We are willing to stand up, speak up, fight for those values together, shoulder-to-shoulder around the world."The ambassador told me he hopes to stay in London through the end of the Obama presidency."I love this job. I love every single day. Best job I've ever had," Barzun said, his youthful face beaming. "And I do serve at the pleasure of the president, so as long as he wants me here I will gladly continue to serve in this capacity until his term is over - and then I go back to Kentucky."To run for office?He laughed. And repeated his last sentence: "I go back to Kentucky.""No, I really haven't figured out what…," he said, trailing off. "There's so much taking up every day, every week, I just don't…there's more than enough to think about and work on and engage with the Brits on every day."But when he's done in London, he said, "the only thing I know is that it's back to Louisville."Reporter James R. Carroll can be reached at (703) 854-8945. Follow him on Twitter @JRCarrollNews.
            
